Introduction

Despite record progress in global healthcare, where a child is born remains one of the most decisive factors in their chances of survival. While neonatal mortality rates (NMR) have fallen over the decades, the pace and extent of improvement vary greatly by region, economy, and access to care. This article presents trends, causes, and inequalities in neonatal mortality â€” and what this reveals about health equity worldwide.

1. A Global Map of Neonatal Risk

This map gives a stark picture of health inequities across the globe by highlighting the average neonatal mortality rates from 2013 to 2022. Countries colored dark red, majorly in African Continent, with a few being in Asia have the highest newborn mortality rates, reflecting compromised healthcare systems and an urgent need for intervention. Lighter regions like Europe, North America, and parts of Oceania are countries with well-maintained healthcare infrastructure and low have NMRs. What is most remarkable is not just the progress made, but the sheer disparity between the nations.

This shows the hard reality - A childâ€™s chances of survival still remain largely conditioned on the location of their birth.

Code 
import polars as pl
from plotnine import *
import geopandas as gp
import pandas as pd

gapminder = pl.read_csv(
    "data_set.csv",
    schema_overrides={"Population_total": pl.Float64}
)
Code 
average_NMR = (gapminder
    .group_by("country")
    .agg(pl.col("NMR_Value").mean().alias("avg_NMR"))
)

shape_world = gp.read_file("https://public.opendatasoft.com/api/explore/v2.1/catalog/datasets/world-administrative-boundaries/exports/shp")

map_NMR = (shape_world
    .merge(average_NMR.to_pandas(), left_on="name", right_on="country", how="outer")
)

(ggplot(data=map_NMR)
    + aes(fill="avg_NMR")
    + geom_map()
    + coord_fixed()
    + scale_fill_gradient(low="green", high="red")
    + theme(text=element_text(size=10, family="Times New Roman"))
    + labs(title="Neonatal Mortality Rate by Country (Average)",
           fill="Average NMR")
)

2. Neonatal Mortality in the Last Decade (2013â€“2022)

Africa has easily been the continent with the highest neonatal mortality rates in the past decade, averaging nearly 25 deaths per 1,000 live births. It is followed by Asia, though at a considerably lower rate, yet one which nonetheless indicates widespread health problems throughout parts of the region. Oceania, North America, and South America cluster around a middle range figure, showing that even relatively wealthier areas have areas of weakness. Europe is the lowest-scoring outlier for neonatal mortality, a testament to its strong, accessible health systems.

While the global trend is towards improvement, these figures point to persisting inequalities: Where a child is born still has a significant impact on their chances of surviving the first month of life.

Code 
gapminder_last_10_years = gapminder.filter(pl.col("year").is_between(2013, 2022))

gapminder_avg_continent_last_10 = (
  gapminder_last_10_years
  .group_by(pl.col("Continent"))
  .agg(
    pl.col("NMR_Value").mean().alias("avg_NMR")
  )

color_map = {
    'Africa': 'red',
    'Asia': 'orange',
    'Europe': 'forestgreen',
    'North America': 'blue',
    'South America': 'purple',
    'Oceania': 'brown'
}

(ggplot(data=gapminder_avg_continent_last_10)
  + aes(x="Continent", y="avg_NMR", fill="Continent")
  + geom_col()
  + scale_fill_manual(values=color_map)
  + theme_matplotlib()
  + theme(text=element_text(size=10, family="Times New Roman"),
          axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=45, hjust=1))
  + labs(title="Average Neonatal Mortality Rate Between 2013-2022", y="Average NMR", x="Continent")

3. Long March of Progress

Looking at history, the global fight against neonatal mortality has not been an easy or short one.

Since 1960:

  • Africa and Asia have both made steady progress, yet both of them still retain much higher rates of neonatal mortality than all other continents.
  • Europe, North America, and Oceania had sharp NMR declines in early years, then leveled off at low points by the late 20th century.
  • South America also saw consistent improvement, in the same trend as Asia but from a lower NMR base.

What is heartening is that all continents have seen dramatic reductions in neonatal mortality over the decades, showing global resilience of innovation, vaccines, healthcare access, and education.

Code 
(

4. Health, Wealth and Survival - A Recent Snapshot (2022)

Zooming in to 2022, the world shows a clear â€” if uneven â€” picture of the relationship between neonatal survival, health, and wealth.

  • In Europe and Oceania, those countries with greater GDP per capita have more life expectancies and fewer neonatal deaths (represented by the small-sized circles). These regions show strong healthcare systems where prosperity has translated into longer, healthier lives.

  • In Africa, it is otherwise. Even at fairly higher GDP levels (in the region), neonatal mortality rates are still high (larger circles), and life expectancy is still not capable of increasing. This highlights that economic growth alone is not enough â€” robust healthcare infrastructure and equitable access are the turnkeys.

  • Asia and South America exhibit a consistent positive trend: With rising GDP, life expectancy rates also rise, and neonatal mortality reduces, although variability across nations remains.

In 2022, wealthier countries live longer and healthier lives, but economic growth must be supplemented with investments in health to actually reduce neonatal mortality and raise life expectancy.

Code 
gapminder_2022 = (
    gapminder
    .filter(pl.col("year") == 2022)
    .select([
        pl.col("country"),
        pl.col("Continent"),
        pl.col("GDP"),
        pl.col("Life expectancy at birth, total (years)"),
        pl.col("NMR_Value")
    ])
    .drop_nulls()
    .to_pandas()
)

(
    ggplot(gapminder_2022)
    + aes(
        x='GDP',
        y='Life expectancy at birth, total (years)',
        size='NMR_Value',
        color='Continent'
    )
    + geom_point(alpha=0.7)
    + scale_x_log10()
    + geom_smooth(method='loess', se=False, color='black')
    + facet_wrap('~Continent')
     + scale_color_manual(values={
        'Africa': 'red',
        'Asia': 'orange',
        'Europe': 'forestgreen',
        'North America': 'blue',
        'South America': 'purple',
        'Oceania': 'brown'
    })
    + scale_x_log10(labels=lambda l: [f'{int(v):,}' for v in l])
    + theme_matplotlib()
      + theme(text=element_text(size=10, family="Times New Roman"))
    + labs(
        title="Correlation Between Mortality, GDP, and Life Expectancy (2022)",
        x="GDP per Capita",
        y="Life Expectancy at Birth (years)",
        size="Neonatal Mortality Rate"
    )
    + theme(figure_size=(10, 6))
)

5. More Births equals More Losses?

The data reveals a distinct global pattern - Countries with higher Neonatal Mortality Rates also have higher birth rates, specifically in Africa and Asia. On the other hand, Europe and North America reveal low NMR and low birth rates, which reflect stronger healthcare systems and higher levels of development.

  • The trendline confirms that as neonatal mortality declines, birth rates also decline but this effect tapers off at very high NMR. Larger countries, particularly in Asia, contribute significantly to world birth rates even where neonatal prospects have improved.

  • This highlights a key link - Investments in health not only reduce infant deaths but also support lower fertility and long-term social and economic progress.

  • Rapid population growth in the past often kept ahead of medical care, even in more prosperous nations. Countries that managed to stabilise population growth over decades were able to advance health gains and sustain healthcare investment.

Higher neonatal mortality is closely tied to higher birth rates and population growth. Investing in healthcare not only saves newborn lives but also drives long-term population and economic shifts.

6. Neonatal Mortality: Leaders vs.Â Lagging Countries

If we look at neonatal mortality over several years, we are seeing patterns above GDP and life expectancy â€” a testament to the profound influence of hospital beds, birth rates, and population growth.

  • San Marino (0.4 NMR), Japan (0.6), and Iceland (0.8) were the leaders in neonatal survival as of 2022. These nations possess world-class healthcare systems, universal coverage of quality care, high-end neonatal services, and strong public health policy. Their low NMRs reflect the benefits of well-funded healthcare, available maternal education, and strong prenatal care, which ensure the survival of newborns.

  • On the other hand, countries like South Sudan, Pakistan, and the Central African Republic have much higher NMRs of more than 32 deaths per 1,000 live births. These nations are going through extended conflict, underfunded health centers, poor sanitation, and malnutrition, all of which lead to excessive neonatal mortality. Inadequate access to healthcare, political instability, and inadequate maternal care continue to hamper progress. These issues highlight the necessity of enhanced healthcare infrastructure and education to promote neonatal outcomes in such regions.

To bridge the gap between top performers and struggling nations, international support and resources are essential. Strengthening healthcare infrastructure and improving maternal care can save countless newborn lives. Global collaboration is key to reducing neonatal mortality worldwide.

Code 
import patchworklib as pw
import polars as pl
from plotnine import *
import pandas as pd

gapminder_2022 = gapminder.filter(pl.col("year") == 2022)

top10_best = gapminder_2022.sort("NMR_Value").head(10).to_pandas()
top10_worst = gapminder_2022.sort("NMR_Value", descending=True).head(10).to_pandas()

top10_best["Category"] = "Best"
top10_worst["Category"] = "Worst"
combined_df = pd.concat([top10_best, top10_worst])

#
plot = (
    ggplot(combined_df, aes(x="NMR_Value", y="reorder(country, NMR_Value)", color="Category"))
    + geom_point(size=4, alpha=0.8)
    + geom_text(
        aes(label="None"),
        nudge_x=1,
        size=8,
        ha='left',
        va='center',
        show_legend=False
    )
    + facet_wrap("~Category", scales="free_x", nrow=1)
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(
        axis_title_y=element_blank(),
        axis_text_y=element_text(size=8),
        axis_text_x=element_text(size=8),
        strip_background=element_rect(fill="#d1d1d1"),
        strip_text=element_text(size=8, weight='bold'),
        panel_spacing=0.8,
        plot_margin={"t": 0.3, "r": 0.3, "b": 0.2, "l": 0.2},
        legend_position='none',
        text=element_text(family="Times New Roman")
    )
    + labs(
        x="Neonatal Mortality Rate (NMR)"
    )
)

pw.load_ggplot(plot)

Conclusion

Neonatal mortality is a significant issue across the globe with glaring inconsistencies between nations. With better wealth and health care, there remain nations with unimproved healthcare infrastructure with high NMRs.The relationship between birth facilities, births, and population growth is critical in the calculation of neonatal survival rates. Bridging these gaps requires international solidarity, ongoing investment in healthcare, and policy to prioritize maternal and neonatal health so that all newborns have an equal chance for survival regardless of where he or she was born.
